		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The proposed programme is the systematic exploration of reaction conditions, drying schedules and doping methods (eg solution; impregnation) so that novel sol-gel materials suitable for the manufacture of nonlinear optical devices can be produced.  Undoped/doped: alkyl, polymerisable group substituted, and UV-curable ormosils; dried xerogels and partially densified silica will be synthesised.  Comparisons will be made on the basis of optical properties, microstructure and material stability.  We shall study a range of organic dye and rare earth dopants and also investigate tailoring of the host's refractive index.  Central to the project is a postdoctoral assistant with experience in chemical processing for whom funds are requested.  To sustain very clean conditions during material fabrication, funds are requested to upgrade to a clean chemical station.  The linear and non-linear optical performance of prepared bulk materials and thin film waveguides will be assessed both inhouse and in collaboration with groups at Durham, Manchester and Heriot-Watt Universities.  Funds are requested for working visits and to establish an inhouse facility for the critical, optical assessment of thin film, planar waveguides.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
